Introduction¶

This report is part of the Advanced Statistical Learning course of the Master 2 TIDE. We have two datasets that combine both quantitative and qualitative data. The goal of this study is to apply techniques that address the problems posed by our data types such as ACM or AFMD for example, combined with other learning approaches for clustering.

Variables meaning :¶

  • Customer_ID
  • Status_checking_Acc :
    • A11 : < 0 USD
    • A12 : between 0 and 10000 USD
    • A13 : > 10000
    • A14 : no checking account
  • Duration_in_Months
  • Credit_History:
    • A30: no credits taken/all credits paid back duly
    • A31: all credits at this bank paid back duly
    • A32: existing credits paid back duly till now
    • A33: delay in paying off in the past
    • A34: critical account/other credits existing(not at this bank)
  • Purpose_Credit_Taken:
    • A40: car (new)
    • A41: car (used)
    • A42: furniture/equipment
    • A43: radio/television
    • A44: domestic appliances
    • A45: repairs
    • A46: education
    • A47: (vacation - does not exist?)
    • A48: retraining
    • A49: business
    • A410: others
  • Credit_Amount
  • Savings_Acc:
    • A61: < 1000 USD
    • A62: 1000 <= < 5000 USD
    • A63: 5000 <= < 10000 USD
    • A64: .. >= 10000 USD
    • A65: unknown/ no savings account
  • Years_At_Present_Employment:
    • A71: unemployed
    • A72: < 1 year
    • A73: 1 <= < 4 years
    • A74: 4 <= < 7 years
    • A75: .. >= 7 years
  • Inst_Rt_Income: installment rate in percentage of disposable income
  • Marital_Status_Gender:
    • A91: male : divorced/separated
    • A92: female: divorced/separated/married
    • A93: male : single
    • A94: male : married/widowed
    • A95: female: single
  • Other_Debtors_Guarantors:
    • A101: none
    • A102: co-applicant
    • A103: guarantor
  • Current_Address_Yrs : Present residence since
  • Property:
    • A121: real estate
    • A122: if not A121: building society savings agreement/life insurance
    • A123: if not A121/A122: car or other, not in attribute 6
    • A124: unknown / no property
  • Age: age in years
  • Other_Inst_Plans: Other installment plans
    • A141: bank
    • A142: stores
    • A143: none
  • Housing:
    • A151: rent
    • A152: own
    • A153: for free
  • Num_CC: number of existing credits at this bank
  • Job:
    • A171: unemployed/ unskilled - non-resident
    • A172: unskilled - resident
    • A173: skilled employee / official
    • A174: management/ self-employed/highly qualified employee/ officer
  • Dependents: number of people being liable to provide maintenance for
  • Telephone:
    • A191: none
    • A192: yes, registered under the customers name
  • Foreign_Worker:
    • A201: yes
    • A202: no
  • Default_On_Payment:
    • 0 : no default
    • 1 : default

Dendrograms to see the number of possible clusters¶

Before trying to do some clustering on the 2 dimensianal space delineated by the variables "Age" and "Credit_Amount", we tryed to identify the number of possible clusters with the help of 4 different dendrograms computed with the ward, single, complete and average methods.

Apart from ward's method dendrogram, all the graphs have one cluster all the way to the left and then a large ramification on the right which starts at different points according to the method but that follows a similar path. Ward's method computed dendrogram has 2 initial ramifications, then it starts ramificating on the right and then on the left. What they have in common is that in general the first ramification (2 clusters) is the longest one, for this reason we tryed to look for 2 clusters with the clustering techniques we used.

Computing Gower's distance matrix¶

https://medium.com/analytics-vidhya/gowers-distance-899f9c4bd553

Since we have both quantitative and qualitative variables, computing distances with qualitative variables as usual is not possible. For this reason we looked for other approaches and we found Gower's distance matrix that can cumpute distances even when we have qualitative variables.

In [302]:
tester = quant
tester["Purposre_Credit_Taken"] = bank["Purposre_Credit_Taken"]
distance_matrix = gower.gower_matrix(tester, cat_features = [False,False,False,False,False,False,False,True])
In [309]:
Zd = linkage(distance_matrix,  method = 'ward') 
dendro = dendrogram(Zd, no_labels=True)
plt.title('Gower with ward linkage')
plt.ylabel('Euclidean distance')
plt.show()

What we did here was to do an agglomerative clustering by giving Gower's computed distance matrix and in this last plot we applyed a PCA to try to see more clearly the 2 clusters identified. We can see that the clustering doesn't appear to follow a linear rule, at least not in the 2-d space we chose which is either delineated by age and credit amount or by the 2 principal components resulting from a PCA done on the 3 variables : Age, Credit_Amount and the qualitative one Purpose_Credit_Taken.

Optics Clustering (derived from DBSCAN)¶

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/OPTICS_algorithm

Since we weren't satisfied by the clustering made with the agglomerative clustering algorithm we tryed other techniques. Here for example we tryed optics clustering which is derived from DBSCAN but allows differentiated cluster densities.

MCA¶

Here we wanted to do Multiple Correspondence Analysis on some of the qualitative variables present in the Bank's dataset. The variables we used are the "Purposre_Credit_Taken", "Foreign_Worker", "Default_On_Payment" and "Credit_History" renominated as "Deafault", "Purpose", "Foreign" and "History".

In [283]:

def scatter_text(x, y, text_column, data, title, xlabel, ylabel):
    """Scatter plot with country codes on the x y coordinates
       Based on this answer: https://stackoverflow.com/a/54789170/2641825"""
    # Create the scatter plot
    p1 = sns.scatterplot(x, y, data=data, size = 8, legend=False)
    # Add text besides each point
    for line in range(0,data.shape[0]):
         p1.text(data[x][line]+0.01, data[y][line], 
                 data[text_column][line], horizontalalignment='left', 
                 size='large', color='black', weight='semibold')
    # Set title and axis labels
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    return p1

# original_df the original numeric dataframe
# pca is the model
def create_importance_dataframe(pca, original_df):

    # Change pcs components ndarray to a dataframe
    importance_df  = pd.DataFrame(pca.components_)

    # Assign columns
    importance_df.columns  = original_df.columns

    # Change to absolute values
    importance_df =importance_df.apply(np.abs)

    # Transpose
    importance_df=importance_df.transpose()

    # Change column names again

    ## First get number of pcs
    num_pcs = importance_df.shape[1]

    ## Generate the new column names
    new_columns = [f'PC{i}' for i in range(1, num_pcs + 1)]

    ## Now rename
    importance_df.columns  =new_columns

    # Return importance df
    return importance_df

corr_matrix = data.corr()
upper_tri = corr_matrix.where(np.triu(np.ones(corr_matrix.shape),k=1).astype(np.bool))
def top_correlation(df,n):
     correlation = upper_tri.stack().sort_values(ascending=False)
     correlation = pd.DataFrame(correlation).reset_index()
     correlation.columns=["Variable 1","Variable 2","Correlation"]
     correlation = correlation.reindex(correlation.Correlation.abs().sort_values(ascending=False).index)
     return correlation.head(n)

def duration_scaled(x):
    if x['Duration_in_Months']>0 and x['Duration_in_Months'] < 10:
        return 0
    elif x['Duration_in_Months']>=10 and x['Duration_in_Months'] < 20:
        return 10
    elif x['Duration_in_Months']>=20 and x['Duration_in_Months'] < 30:
        return 20
    elif x['Duration_in_Months']>=30 and x['Duration_in_Months'] < 40:
        return 30
    elif x['Duration_in_Months']>=40 and x['Duration_in_Months'] < 50:
        return 40
    elif x['Duration_in_Months']>=50 and x['Duration_in_Months'] < 60:
        return 50
    elif x['Duration_in_Months']>=60 and x['Duration_in_Months'] < 70:
        return 60
    else :
        return 70

data['Duration_in_Months_scaled'] = data.apply(duration_scaled, axis = 1)

Manage imbalances dataset

The data is imbalanced (less than 30% of the data is defaulted). There are four main methods to manage imbalanced:

  • Undersampling : random undersample data (we don't have enough data to use this method)
  • Oversampling : oversample data with many techniques
  • Sample weighting: we play on the cost function to penalize when it makes an error in the minority class
  • Stratify : use of stratify during the train test split

Checking missing values in columns¶

we calculate the proportion of missing values in all columns and first deleted variables with 80% of missing values, then 50%, to finally delete columns with 20% of missing values as we preferred deleting columns than lines of observation. We don't know the meaning of most of the features and we still have 166 variables in our dataset. It was not easy to decide to delete 323 features

Filling missing data with mean observation¶

We could not delete all the columns with missing values, or we won't remain with a very interesting dataset. So, for the remaining missing values, we will fill them with the mean value. Of course, this doesn't work with categorical values, but we are lucky, we don't have any missing values in the categorical variables.

Isolating numerical variables by using the types, here we choose to select features with float type. As we fear that some integer type can be actually categorical (for example region).

FAMD¶

As our dataset has mix type of features and as we want to reduce the dimensionality, we instinctively tried an FAMD (Factor Analysis of Mixed Data). The result is not very interesting, as we can't really distinguish clusters. We reduce on two components and they explain less than 10% of the variance. We suppose that our method of dealing with missing values didn't work well.

In [108]:
from prince import FAMD
famd = FAMD(n_components =2, n_iter = 3, random_state = 101)

famd.transform(df_famd)
famd.plot_row_coordinates(df_famd,figsize=(15, 10),color_labels=['Type of firm : {}'.format(t) for t in df_famd['pavitt']] ) ;

Filling missing data with KNN method¶

Instead of simply filling missing data with mean or median, we thought that looking for 3 nearest neighbors of each missing value can be a better strategy. As we will see, it was quite a deception, maybe we deleted too much columns for our dataset initially.

def scatter_text(x, y, text_column, data, title, xlabel, ylabel):
    """Scatter plot with country codes on the x y coordinates
       Based on this answer: https://stackoverflow.com/a/54789170/2641825"""
    # Create the scatter plot
    p1 = sns.scatterplot(x, y, data=data, size = 8, legend=False)
    # Add text besides each point
    for line in range(0,data.shape[0]):
         p1.text(data[x][line]+0.01, data[y][line], 
                 data[text_column][line], horizontalalignment='left', 
                 size='large', color='black', weight='semibold')
    # Set title and axis labels
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    return p1
